<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-01-13T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-01-13T17:00:00-05:00" n="719" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d719">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.672/537: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the High Commissioner in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bristol</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-01-13T17:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">January 13,
                                        1927—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>6. Your telegram No. 5, January 13, noon. You should discreetly do
                            everything you can to dispel any idea that advice and consent to the
                            ratification of the treaty by the Senate is a foregone conclusion,
                            indicating that at the present time opposition is particularly active
                            and strong.</p>
                        <p>In view of the possibility set forth in the Department’s No. 5, January
                            11, 6 p.m., undue optimism in Turkish circles in regard to the approval
                            of the treaty would be more regrettable.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>